-- The library provides a proof that Markov's principle follows from Stone Duality.
-- Here we show how to use it and state additional consequences.

-- Markov's principle: if a sequence is not all zeros, we can find a one.
-- This is proved in OmnisciencePrinciples.Markov from Stone Duality via
-- the observation that if őĪ ‚ČĘ 0, then Sp(2/őĪ) is inhabited.

-- Assuming Stone Duality, we can derive MP:
-- From Stone Duality: evaluation map B ‚Üí 2^(Sp B) is an equivalence for B : BooleŌČ
-- Given őĪ : 2^‚Ąē with ¬¨(‚ąÄn. őĪn = 0), consider the quotient 2/őĪ.
-- If Sp(2/őĪ) were inhabited, we'd have a map 2/őĪ ‚Üí 2,
-- but this would make őĪ identically 0, contradiction.
-- So Sp(2/őĪ) is empty, meaning 0 = 1 in 2/őĪ, meaning some őĪn = 1.

-- =============================================================================
-- Section 13: LLPO from Stone Duality
-- =============================================================================

-- The proof of LLPO from Stone Duality (see main-monolithic.tex) goes as follows:
--
-- 1. B_‚ąě is the Boolean algebra generated by (g_n)_{n:‚Ąē} with relations g_m ‚ąß g_n = 0 for m ‚Č† n.
--    Its spectrum ‚Ąē‚ąě = Sp(B_‚ąě) consists of sequences hitting 1 at most once.
--
-- 2. Define f : B_‚ąě ‚Üí B_‚ąě √ó B_‚ąě by:
--    f(g_n) = (g_k, 0) if n = 2k
--    f(g_n) = (0, g_k) if n = 2k+1
--
-- 3. This map is injective (well-defined by the relations).
--
-- 4. By Stone Duality axiom "surjections are formal surjections":
--    f injective ‚üĻ Sp(f) : Sp(B_‚ąě √ó B_‚ąě) ‚Üí Sp(B_‚ąě) is surjective.
--
-- 5. Since Sp(B_‚ąě √ó B_‚ąě) ‚ČÖ ‚Ąē‚ąě + ‚Ąē‚ąě, we get a surjection s : ‚Ąē‚ąě + ‚Ąē‚ąě ‚Üí ‚Ąē‚ąě.
--
-- 6. For any őĪ : ‚Ąē‚ąě, there exists x : ‚Ąē‚ąě + ‚Ąē‚ąě with s(x) = őĪ.
--    - If x = inl(ő≤), then őĪ_{2k+1} = 0 for all k.
--    - If x = inr(ő≤), then őĪ_{2k} = 0 for all k.

-- We postulate LLPO as an axiom that follows from Stone Duality.
-- The full proof requires setting up B_‚ąě quotients which is done in the library.

postulate
  llpo : LLPO

-- =============================================================================
-- Section 14: Consequences of LLPO
-- =============================================================================

-- LLPO implies that closed propositions are closed under finite disjunctions.
-- This is because LLPO is equivalent to the statement:
-- (¬¨P ‚ą® ¬¨Q) ‚ÜĒ ¬¨(P ‚ąß Q) for open P, Q

-- Given P, Q closed propositions:
-- P ‚ÜĒ ‚ąÄn. őĪn = 0, Q ‚ÜĒ ‚ąÄn. ő≤n = 0
-- We want: P ‚ą® Q is closed.
--
-- P ‚ą® Q ‚ÜĒ (‚ąÄn. őĪn = 0) ‚ą® (‚ąÄn. ő≤n = 0)
--
-- Define ő≥ : ‚Ąē‚ąě by: ő≥(2k) = őĪ(k), ő≥(2k+1) = ő≤(k)
-- (But ő≥ may hit 1 more than once if both őĪ and ő≤ hit 1.)
--
-- Instead, we use LLPO on sequences that hit at most once.

-- For the full characterization, we would prove:
-- LLPO ‚ÜĒ "For open P, Q: (¬¨P ‚ą® ¬¨Q) ‚ÜĒ ¬¨(P ‚ąß Q)"
--
-- This is Proposition 1.4.1 of Diener's book on constructive reverse mathematics.

-- Closed propositions closed under disjunction (using LLPO)
-- The direct proof is more involved; we sketch the idea:

-- Given őĪ, ő≤ : 2^‚Ąē witnessing closedness of P, Q:
-- P ‚ÜĒ ‚ąÄn. őĪn = 0, Q ‚ÜĒ ‚ąÄn. ő≤n = 0
--
-- To show P ‚ą® Q is closed, we need ő≥ : 2^‚Ąē with:
-- (P ‚ą® Q) ‚ÜĒ ‚ąÄn. ő≥n = 0
--
-- The issue is P ‚ą® Q = (‚ąÄn. őĪn = 0) ‚ą® (‚ąÄn. ő≤n = 0), which is NOT the same as
-- ‚ąÄn. (őĪn = 0 ‚ą® ő≤n = 0) (the latter is weaker).
--
-- LLPO bridges this gap for suitable sequences.

-- For now, we postulate closedOr as following from LLPO:
